  1. Creating vector of colors to be implemented in our plots

  1. Reading the Data into their designated variables
apr <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-apr14.csv")
may <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-may14.csv")
jun <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-jun14.csv")
jul <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-jul14.csv")
aug <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-aug14.csv")
sep <- read.csv("/Users/ruthb/Desktop/Dory's Projects/Uber Project/Uber-dataset/uber-raw-data-sep14.csv")
  1. Combine all of this data into a single data frame called data
data <- rbind(apr, may, jun, jul, aug, sep)
View(data)
  1. Formatting of Date.Time column
data$Date.Time <- as.POSIXct(data$Date.Time, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S")
data$Time <- format(as.POSIXct(data$Date.Time, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M:%S"), format="%H:%M:%S")
data$Date.Time <- ymd_hms(data$Date.Time)
data$day <- factor(day(data$Date.Time))
data$month <- factor(month(data$Date.Time, label = TRUE))
data$year <- factor(year(data$Date.Time))
data$dayofweek <- factor(wday(data$Date.Time, label = TRUE))
  1. Create factors of time objects like day, month, year etc.
data$hour <- factor(hour(hms(data$Time)))
data$minute <- factor(minute(hms(data$Time)))
data$second <- factor(second(hms(data$Time)))
  1. Plotting the trips by the hours in a day. We observe that the number of trips are higher in the evening around 5:00 and 6:00 PM.
hour <- data %>%
        group_by(hour) %>%
        dplyr::summarize(Total = n()) 
datatable(hour)
  1. We will use dplyr to aggregate our data.
ggplot(hour, aes(hour, Total)) + 
        geom_bar( stat = "identity", fill = "black", color = "red") +
           ggtitle("Trips Every Hour") +
            theme(legend.position = "none") +
            scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

month_hour <- data %>%
          group_by(month, hour) %>%
             dplyr::summarize(Total = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(month_hour, aes(hour, Total, fill = month)) + 
       geom_bar( stat = "identity") +
          ggtitle("Trips by Hour and Month") +
           scale_y_continuous(labels = comma)

  1. Plotting data by trips during every day of the month. We observe that 30th of the month had the highest trips in the year which is mostly contributed by the month of April.

  1. Finding out the number of Trips by bases In the following visualization, we plot the number of trips that have been taken by the passengers from each of the bases. There are five bases in all out of which, we observe that B02617 had the highest number of trips. Furthermore, this base had the highest number of trips in the month B02617. Thursday observed highest trips in the three bases B02598, B02617, B02682.
ggplot(data, aes(Base)) + 
 geom_bar(fill = "black", color = "red") +
 scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
 ggtitle("Trips by Bases")

ggplot(data, aes(Base, fill = month)) + 
 geom_bar(position = "dodge") +
 scale_y_continuous(labels = comma) +
 ggtitle("Trips by Bases and Month") +
 scale_fill_manual(values = colors)

 geom_bar(position = "dodge") +

 ggtitle("Trips by Bases and DayofWeek") +

  1. Creating a Heatmap visualization of day, hour and month First, we will plot Heatmap by Hour and Day. Second, we will plot Heatmap by Month and Day. Third, a Heatmap by Month and Day of the Week. Fourth, a Heatmap that delineates Month and Bases. Finally, we will plot the heatmap, by bases and day of the week.
day_hour <- data %>%
         group_by(day, hour) %>%
            dplyr::summarize(Total = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'day'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
datatable(day_hour)
ggplot(day_hour, aes(day, hour, fill = Total)) +
            geom_tile(color = "black") +
              ggtitle("Heat Map by Hour and Day")

ggplot(day_month, aes(day, month, fill = Total)) +
            geom_tile(color = "black") +
              ggtitle("Heat Map by Month and Day")

ggplot(month_weekday, aes(dayofweek, month, fill = Total)) +
            geom_tile(color = "black") +
              ggtitle("Heat Map by Month and Day of Week")

month_base <-  data %>%
               group_by(Base, month) %>%
               dplyr::summarize(Total = n()) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Base'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
dayofweek_bases <- data %>%
                   group_by(Base, dayofweek) %>%
                   dplyr::summarize(Total = n()) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Base'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
ggplot(month_base, aes(Base, month, fill = Total)) +
            geom_tile(color = "black") +
              ggtitle("Heat Map by Month and Bases")

ggplot(dayofweek_bases, aes(Base, dayofweek, fill = Total)) +
            geom_tile(color = "black") +
              ggtitle("Heat Map by Bases and Day of Week")

  1. Creating a map visualization of rides in New York In the final section, we will visualize the rides in New York city by creating a geo-plot that will help us to visualize the rides during 2014 (AprSep) and by the bases in the same period.
min_lat <- 40.5774
max_lat <- 40.9176
min_long <- -74.15
max_long <- -73.7004

ggplot(data, aes(x=Lon, y=Lat)) +
  geom_point(size=1, color = "black") +
     scale_x_continuous(limits=c(min_long, max_long)) +
      scale_y_continuous(limits=c(min_lat, max_lat)) +
        theme_map() +
           ggtitle("NYC MAP BASED ON UBER RIDES DURING 2014 (APR-SEP)")
